svg.title: We were promised Xanadu! An Infrastructure-Agnostic Model of Hypertext

cc:Work.dc:title: We were promised Xanadu! An Infrastructure-Agnostic Model of Hypertext
cc:Work.dc:description: Poster presented at the 30th ACM Conference on Hypertext and Social Media (HT’19) 17–20 September 2019 Hof, Germany

text.tspan: 30th ACM Conference on Hypertext and Social Media (HT’19) 17–20 September 2019 Hof, Germany — 30 Years of Hypertext

flowPara.style: font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;font-stretch:normal;font-size:34.66666794px;font-family:'OFL Sorts Mill Goudy';-inkscape-font-specification:'OFL Sorts Mill Goudy';text-align:start;text-anchor:start

flowRoot.flowPara: Former hypertext systems rarely capture the original idea of hypertext. The elephant in the room is transclusion: segments of existing documents must be locatable and combinable into new documents.

text.tspan: Xanadu® and the Eternal-Flaming-X logo are registered trademarks of Project Xanadu. Vague, but exciting is a note by Mike Sendall on Tim Berners-Lee's hypertext proposal. Fonts by Barry Schwartz (The League of Moveable Type) based on Frederic Goudy's typefaces.

flowRoot.flowPara: This model is agnostic to specific technologies and data formats, which come and go with progress and hypes. User interfaces and copyright enforcement can also be added on top.

flowRoot.flowPara: Decentralized hypertext systems can be implemented based on existing technologies, especially the Web. R&D is required to support content locators and edit lists for all kinds of document models.
